{
  "doc_id": "7251",
  "text": "On the other hand, pyrazines could be formed when ammonia or amino acids react with a-dicarbonyl compounds to form a-amino carbonyl compound, which is the precursor for pyrazine formation. Both carbohydrate and lipid could be the source for a-dicarbonyl compounds in marine PL. It is no doubt that a-amino carbonyl compounds could be formed through the Strecker degradation of amino acids by methylglyoxal or glyoxal (a-dicarbonyl compound derived from sugar or carbohydrates). Nevertheless, methylglyoxal and glyoxal have been shown to be lipid oxidation products in system containing no reducing sugar [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Therefore, the formation of pyrazines in marine PL is partly attributed to the presence of lipid oxidation products. In addition, [CITATION_3] reported that the presence of lipid oxidation products greatly influenced the formation of pyrazines in model system containing vegetable oils, lysine, xylose, and glucose. In addition, it is important to note that pyrazines formation in marine PL could be associated with the incomplete removal of shell during marine PL manufacturing process. Our previous study reported that the formation of pyrazines and its alkyl substituents in krill oil was partly attributed to the presence of residual krill shell in krill oil [CITATION_4] .",
